---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';
---

<CaseStudyLayout title="Case Study: Architecting an Engagement Engine | Kunal Katre">
    
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <div class="not-prose mb-12 animate-fade-in">
        <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-12 items-center">
            <div class="flex-1 space-y-6">
                 <a href="/#work" class="btn btn-ghost btn-sm gap-2 pl-0 hover:bg-transparent hover:text-primary transition-colors duration-300">
                    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M19 12H5"/><path d="M12 19l-7-7 7-7"/></svg>
                    Back to Work
                </a>
                
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-sm font-medium text-base-content/70">
                    <span>Project for</span>
                    <img src="/assets/eka-logo.svg" alt="Eka Care logo" class="h-6 w-auto" />
                </div>

                <h1 class="text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-serif font-bold leading-tight">
                    Architecting an Engagement Engine
                </h1>
                
                <p class="text-xl text-base-content/80 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
                    I transformed a failing feature with 38% user drop-off into a core driver of engagement and retention for the Eka.Care platform.
                </p>

                <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4 pt-4">
                    <div class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300 backdrop-blur-sm">
                        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary">+21%</div>
                        <div class="text-sm text-base-content/70">Conversion Lift</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300 backdrop-blur-sm">
                        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary">2x</div>
                        <div class="text-sm text-base-content/70">Week 4 Retention</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300 backdrop-blur-sm">
                        <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-accent">4 Months</div>
                        <div class="text-sm text-base-content/70">Oct – Jan 2023</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="flex-1 w-full max-w-md lg:max-w-full flex justify-center">
                <div class="mockup-phone border-primary">
                    <div class="camera"></div> 
                    <div class="display">
                        <div class="artboard artboard-demo phone-1 bg-black overflow-hidden relative">
                             <!-- Video Content -->
                             <video src="/assets/hr/instruction video-1.mp4" autoplay loop muted playsinline poster="/assets/hr/result-final-dashboard.png" class="w-full h-full object-cover"></video>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="space-y-16">
        
        <!-- Section 1 -->
        <section id="setup">
            <h2>1. The Setup: A Leaky Funnel & a Crisis of Trust</h2>
            <p>In late 2022, the Heart Rate Monitor (BPM) was a strategic bet on organic growth and user engagement. The business objective was two-fold: create a "wow" moment for <strong>first-time users</strong> to drive acquisition, and build a valuable tool that <strong>repeat users</strong> would integrate into their health routines.</p>
            <p>However, analytics painted a grim picture. The feature was underperforming dramatically. Our primary business metrics were failing:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>First-Time User Conversion:</strong> A catastrophic ~38% of users were dropping off before successfully completing their first measurement.</li>
                <li><strong>Long-Term Retention:</strong> Churn analysis showed that even users who were successful once rarely came back. The feature wasn't "sticking."</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2 -->
        <section id="research">
             <h2>2. Discovery: Uncovering the 'Why'</h2>
             <h3>2.1 Guerilla Research: Hearing the User's Voice</h3>
             <p>The data showed *what* was happening, but not *why*. I initiated a quick guerilla research sprint, conducting informal usability tests with a diverse user group. The unfiltered feedback was raw and illuminating.</p>
             
            <figure>
                <img src="/assets/hr/research.png" alt="Guerilla Research in progress" class="w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg border border-base-300">
                <figcaption>Fig. 1 - Conducting informal usability tests to quickly gather qualitative insights.</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 my-8 not-prose">
                <div class="card bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body p-6">
                        <h4 class="card-title text-base mb-2">Instruction Mismatch</h4>
                        <p class="text-sm italic text-base-content/80">"I see the instructions, but I don't understand them. The words are difficult and I don't know which camera to use."</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body p-6">
                        <h4 class="card-title text-base mb-2">The "Phone Flip" Behavior</h4>
                        <p class="text-sm italic text-base-content/80">"It’s hard to do without looking at the back!"</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body p-6">
                        <h4 class="card-title text-base mb-2">Trust & Accuracy Concerns</h4>
                        <p class="text-sm italic text-base-content/80">"I just came from running, but my heart rate shown is 58. I don't trust the reading."</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>2.3 Synthesizing with a User Journey Map</h3>
            <p>I consolidated all these findings into an Emotional Journey Map. This artifact was crucial for stakeholder alignment, as it translated abstract data and user quotes into a clear narrative of declining trust.</p>
            
            <figure>
                <img src="/assets/hr/FTUX-journey-map.webp" alt="Emotional journey map diagnosing the V1 experience" class="w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg border border-base-300">
                <figcaption>Fig. 2 - This map diagnosed the V1 experience, becoming our shared source of truth.</figcaption>
            </figure>
             <figure>
                <img src="/assets/hr/RTUX-journey-map.webp" alt="V1 Returning User Experience journey map" class="w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg border border-base-300">
                <figcaption>Fig. 3 - Diagnosing the V1 Returning User Experience revealed a broken loop with no long-term value.</figcaption>
            </figure>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 3 -->
        <section id="goals">
            <h2>3. Defining the Design Goals</h2>
            <p>With a deep, evidence-backed understanding of the problem, I established three clear, measurable design goals that would guide our entire redesign effort:</p>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 my-8 not-prose">
                <div class="card bg-base-100/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <div class="text-6xl font-serif text-base-content/10 absolute top-4 right-4">1</div>
                        <h3 class="card-title text-xl mb-2 relative z-10">First-Try Success</h3>
                        <p class="relative z-10 text-base-content/80">Overhaul the onboarding and measurement experience to be foolproof, intuitive, and anxiety-free for all users.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-base-100/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body">
                          <div class="text-6xl font-serif text-base-content/10 absolute top-4 right-4">2</div>
                        <h3 class="card-title text-xl mb-2 relative z-10">Unshakeable Trust</h3>
                        <p class="relative z-10 text-base-content/80">Provide transparent, real-time feedback and proactively educate users to eliminate confusion and build confidence in the result.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-base-100/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="card-body">
                          <div class="text-6xl font-serif text-base-content/10 absolute top-4 right-4">3</div>
                        <h3 class="card-title text-xl mb-2 relative z-10">Create a Habit Loop</h3>
                        <p class="relative z-10 text-base-content/80">Transform the results screen from a dead end into an actionable, insightful launchpad that provides clear value and encourages repeat usage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Section 4 -->
        <section id="design">
             <h2>4. Iteration & Design</h2>
             <p>To tackle our goals, I mapped specific design interventions to each stage of the user journey. This strategic diagram guided our design exploration.</p>
             
             <!-- Onboarding -->
             <h3>4.1 Solving for 'First-Try' Success: An Onboarding Deep-Dive</h3>
             <p>Fixing the 38% drop-off required a multi-point attack on the onboarding journey. I broke the problem down into distinct intervention points and explored solutions for each.</p>

             <div class="card bg-base-200/30 border border-base-300 my-8 overflow-hidden">
                <figure class="w-full aspect-video bg-base-300 flex items-center justify-center">
                     <!-- Placeholder or use video from assets if available otherwise use image -->
                     <video src="/assets/hr/instruction video-1.mp4" controls class="w-full h-full object-contain"></video>
                </figure>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h4 class="card-title">The "Wow" Moment Video</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm">We combined technical clarity with human warmth. The final video is fast-paced, human-centric, and crucially includes a "5M+ Readings Recorded" social proof element to instantly build trust.</p>
                </div>
             </div>

             <!-- Error Handling -->
              <h3>Designing a Proactive Safety Net</h3>
               <p>My analysis showed that V1 handled errors passively—it only told the user *after* they had already failed. I explored a more proactive approach to prevent failure before it happens.</p>
              
               <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
                   <figure>
                       <img src="/assets/hr/error-handling-passive.webp" alt="Passive error handling" class="rounded-xl border border-base-300">
                       <figcaption>Before: Passive Handling</figcaption>
                   </figure>
                   <figure>
                       <img src="/assets/hr/error-handling-active.webp" alt="Active error handling" class="rounded-xl border border-base-300">
                       <figcaption>After: Active real-time feedback</figcaption>
                   </figure>
               </div>

             <!-- Results Screen -->
             <h3>4.3 Designing an Actionable Result</h3>
              <p>Fixing the measurement was half the battle. To drive retention, I redesigned the result screen to transform it from a dead-end data point into a rich, contextual health dashboard.</p>
              
              <figure>
                <img src="/assets/hr/result-final.png" alt="Full scrollable view of the final heart rate result screen dashboard" class="w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg border border-base-300">
                <figcaption>The Final Result: A Unified Health Dashboard.</figcaption>
            </figure>

        </section>

        <!-- Section 5 -->
        <section id="impact">
             <h2>5. Impact & Learnings</h2>
             <h3>Positioning Eka as a Trustworthy Health Partner</h3>
             <p>This initiative was more than a redesign; it was a strategic turnaround. By grounding our decisions in deep user research and data, we transformed a failing feature into a core pillar of the Eka.Care experience.</p>
             
             <div class="grid grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 not-prose my-8">
                <div class="stats shadow bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="stat">
                        <div class="stat-title">First-Time User Success</div>
                        <div class="stat-value text-primary">21%</div>
                        <div class="stat-desc">Increase in conversion</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="stats shadow bg-base-200/50 border border-base-300">
                    <div class="stat">
                        <div class="stat-title">Week 4 Retention</div>
                        <div class="stat-value text-secondary">2x</div>
                        <div class="stat-desc">Doubled engagement</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
             </div>

             <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
             <ul>
                 <li><strong>Trust is the Ultimate Metric.</strong> A 'wow' feature that fails is worse than no feature at all. In health tech, flawless execution and trust are more important than novelty.</li>
                 <li><strong>Design is the Synthesizer.</strong> My role went far beyond pixels. I was responsible for connecting the dots between quantitative analytics, qualitative feedback, and business strategy.</li>
                 <li><strong>Retention is a System.</strong> Lasting impact came from designing the *entire system* around retention—from contextual results to trends.</li>
             </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Next Project CTA -->
        <div class="not-prose mt-24">
             <div class="divider"></div>
            <div class="card bg-base-200/50 hover:bg-base-200 transition-colors border border-base-300 cursor-pointer group">
                <a href="/case-studies/cowin" class="card-body flex-row items-center gap-6">
                    <div class="flex-1">
                        <div class="text-sm font-bold opacity-60 uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">Next Case Study</div>
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold group-hover:text-primary transition-colors">Designing for a Nation in Crisis</h3>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-base-content/70">How I used rapid research to transform API chaos into a clear, trustworthy experience for millions.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="hidden md:block">
                         <span class="btn btn-primary btn-circle">
                             <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
                         </span>
                    </div>
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>
</CaseStudyLayout>
